'''Artist Management Group''' ('''AMG''') was a pioneering artist's representation company founded by former [[Creative Artists Agency|CAA]] head [[Michael Ovitz]], [[Rick Yorn]], and [[Julie Yorn]]. [[Jeff Kwatinetz]] of [[The Firm, Inc.|The Firm]] acquired Ovitz' share and merged the two firms in 2002.<ref>{{Citation | last = Waxman | first = Sharon | title = Leading Hollywood Talent and Marketing Companies Merge | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = March 19, 2004 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/19/business/leading-hollywood-talent-and-marketing-companies-merge.html?exprod=permalink&partner=permalink }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Holson | first = Laura | last2 = Weinraub | first2 = Bernard | title = Some See a Young Ovitz in Emerging Power Broker | newspaper = The New York Times | date = May 13, 2002 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/13/business/some-see-a-young-ovitz-in-emerging-power-broker.html?exprod=permalink&partner=permalink }}</ref>
AMG was a pioneering company with respect to talent management. Previously, powerful talent agencies were known more as large companies while management was handled more personally by smaller outfits. Now there are several companies, such as Management 360, [[Mosaic Media Group]], [[Untitled Entertainment]] and [[Steve Golin#Anonymous Content|Anonymous Content]], which function like AMG did.{{Citation needed|date=September 2014}}
